[2
Date: 28 Nov 2001 11:51
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AP Online

Suspected letter's origin
-------------------------------
BERN, Switzerland -- Swiss Federal Police Office said the letter was part
of a large mailing sent on behalf of a Florida company by the New York
branch of the Swiss Post Office. Swiss Post International Inc. provides
worldwide bulk mailing services for companies. Under United States rules,
letters sent within the country by international post offices must carry a
foreign postmark. The letter sent to Chile bore a postmark from Zurich,
Switzerland, but had no date -- typical of letters sent by the New York
branch, Swiss officials said.
On Tuesday, officials at Mosby Inc., a publisher of medical journals, told
the Orlando Sentinel that whoever mailed the letter listed their Orlando,
Florida, headquarters as the return address. Mosby is one of 3 publishing
imprints owned by Harcourt Health Sciences.
[Other reports had this as an ordinary posting under the circumstances of
international bulk mailing, but it was noted that the envelope had 2 naked
windows for the sender and receiver addresses, that is, there was no clear
plastic covering. Thus powder inside the envelope could have fallen out,
and contamination could occur from outside. - Mod.MHJ
